@node Quick Start
@chapter Quick Start

@cindex quick start
@cindex hello world
@cindex first program

Congratulations! You're about to write your first computer program. We'll
start with something simple but complete. By the end of this chapter,
you'll have a working program that you can compile and run.

@section Understanding Program Structure

Before we write code, let's understand how COBOL programs are organized.
Think of a COBOL program like a recipe book with specific sections:

@table @asis
@item IDENTIFICATION DIVISION
The title page - tells us what this program is
@item ENVIRONMENT DIVISION
The kitchen setup - tells us what tools we need
@item DATA DIVISION
The ingredient list - defines our data storage
@item PROCEDURE DIVISION
The cooking instructions - the actual program logic
@end table

@section Your First Program: Score Counter

Let's create a simple program that counts from 1 to 10 and displays each
number. This will teach us about variables, loops, and output.

Create a file called @file{counter.cob} with this content:

@example
IDENTIFICATION DIVISION.
PROGRAM-ID. Score-Counter.

DATA DIVISION.
WORKING-STORAGE SECTION.
01 Current-Score PIC 9 VALUE 0.
01 Final-Score PIC 9 VALUE 1.
01 Display-Message PIC X(20) VALUE "Score: ".

PROCEDURE DIVISION.
Main-Program.
    PERFORM Count-Up UNTIL Current-Score = Final-Score
    DISPLAY "Game Complete!"
    GOBACK.

Count-Up.
    ADD 1 TO Current-Score
    DISPLAY Display-Message Current-Score
    GOBACK.

END PROGRAM Score-Counter.
@end example

Let's break this down line by line:

@table @code
@item IDENTIFICATION DIVISION.
This marks the beginning of our program's identity section
@item PROGRAM-ID. Score-Counter.
We name our program "Score-Counter"
@item DATA DIVISION.
Here we define our data storage (like ingredients)
@item WORKING-STORAGE SECTION.
This is where we declare variables that exist for the whole program
@item 01 Current-Score PIC 9 VALUE 0.
A variable to hold our current score, starts at 0
@item 01 Final-Score PIC 9 VALUE 1.
The score we want to reach
@item 01 Display-Message PIC X(20) VALUE "Score: ".
Text to display before our score
@item PROCEDURE DIVISION.
The actual program logic begins here
@item Main-Program.
Our main procedure (like the main recipe)
@item PERFORM Count-Up UNTIL Current-Score = Final-Score
Keep counting until we reach the final score
@item DISPLAY "Game Complete!"
Show a completion message
@item GOBACK.
Return from this procedure
@item Count-Up.
A subroutine that does the counting
@item ADD 1 TO Current-Score
Increase the score by 1
@item DISPLAY Display-Message Current-Score
Show "Score: " followed by the current number
@end table

@section Compiling Your Program

Now let's turn this COBOL program into assembly code that a computer can
understand.

In your Lisp environment, load EIGHTBOL and compile:

@example
;; Load EIGHTBOL
(asdf:load-system :eightbol)

;; Compile for the 6502 processor (Atari 7800/NES)
;; Include copybook directories for COPY statements
(eightbol:compile-file "counter.cob" :cpu 6502
                       :include '("Source/Generated" "Source/Classes"))
@end example

This creates a file called @file{counter.s} containing 6502 assembly code.

@section Understanding the Output

Let's look at a small part of what the compiler generates:

@example
;;; MOVE 0 TO Current-Score
LDA #0
STA Current-Score

;;; ADD 1 TO Current-Score
LDA Current-Score
CLC
ADC #1
STA Current-Score
@end example

See how each COBOL instruction becomes several assembly instructions?
This is normal - COBOL is a high-level language that the compiler
translates into low-level machine code.

@section Running Your Program

The assembly code needs to be assembled into machine code and run on
the target platform. This usually involves:

@enumerate
@item Using an assembler (like CA65 for 6502)
@item Linking with system libraries
@item Running on an emulator or real hardware
@end enumerate

For learning purposes, you can examine the generated assembly code to
see how your COBOL translates to machine instructions.

@section Try This!

Modify the counter program to count down from 10 to 1 instead of up.
Hint: Use SUBTRACT instead of ADD, and change the UNTIL condition.

@section What You Learned

In this chapter, you learned:

@itemize
@item How COBOL programs are structured into divisions
@item How to declare variables with PIC clauses
@item How to use PERFORM for looping
@item How to display output
@item How to compile COBOL to assembly
@end itemize

Great job on your first program! In the next chapter, we'll dive deeper
into variables and data types.

@node Language Reference
@chapter Language Reference

@cindex language reference
@cindex syntax
@cindex COBOL features

Now that you understand the basics, let's explore COBOL's features in detail.
We'll build your understanding step by step, with examples you can try.

@section The Recipe Book: Program Structure

Imagine a COBOL program as a cookbook. Just like a cookbook has sections
for ingredients and instructions, a COBOL program has divisions that
organize different types of information.

@example
IDENTIFICATION DIVISION.    @c What is this program?
PROGRAM-ID. My-First-Game.

DATA DIVISION.               @c What data do we need?
WORKING-STORAGE SECTION.
01 Player-Score PIC 9(5) VALUE 0.

PROCEDURE DIVISION.          @c What steps do we take?
Main-Loop.
    ADD 100 TO Player-Score
    DISPLAY "Score: " Player-Score
    GOBACK.
@end example

Each division has a specific purpose:

@table @asis
@item IDENTIFICATION DIVISION
Like the title page - tells us what this program is
@item DATA DIVISION
Like the ingredient list - defines our data storage
@item PROCEDURE DIVISION
Like the cooking steps - the actual program logic
@end table

@section Naming Your Program

Every COBOL program needs an identity. This is like giving your recipe
a name and author.

@example
IDENTIFICATION DIVISION.
PROGRAM-ID. Space-Invaders-Clone.
AUTHOR. Your Name Here.
DATE-WRITTEN. 2024.
@end example

The @code{PROGRAM-ID} is required and must be unique. Think of it as
your program's first and last name.

For object-oriented programming, EIGHTBOL supports:

@table @code
@item CLASS-ID. name.
Defines a class (like a blueprint for objects)
@item METHOD-ID. name.
Defines a method within a class
@end table

@example
IDENTIFICATION DIVISION.
CLASS-ID. Player-Character.
AUTHOR. Game Developer.
DATE-WRITTEN. 2024.
@end example

@section Storing Information: Variables

Variables are like containers that hold data. In COBOL, we declare
variables in the DATA DIVISION, just like listing ingredients before
cooking.

@subsection Understanding PIC Clauses

PIC (Picture) clauses describe what kind of data a variable can hold.
Think of them as labels on storage containers.

@example
DATA DIVISION.
WORKING-STORAGE SECTION.
01 Player-Name PIC X(20).        @c Up to 20 letters
01 Player-Score PIC 9(5).        @c 5-digit number (0-99999)
01 Game-Over-Flag PIC X.         @c Single character: 'Y' or 'N'
01 Bonus-Multiplier PIC 9V9.     @c Decimal number: 1.5, 2.0, etc.
@end example

@table @code
@item PIC X
Single character (letter or symbol)
@item PIC X(n)
String of n characters
@item PIC 9
Single digit (0-9)
@item PIC 9(n)
n-digit number
@item PIC 9V9
Decimal number (like 1.5)
@end table

@strong{Important:} EIGHTBOL doesn't support string variables (PIC X).
Use byte arrays or numeric variables instead.

@subsection Giving Variables Initial Values

Use the VALUE clause to set starting values:

@example
01 Player-Health PIC 9(3) VALUE 100.
01 Player-Name PIC X(15) VALUE "Hero".
01 Game-Paused PIC X VALUE 'N'.
@end example

@subsection Try This: Variable Declaration

Create variables for a simple game character:

@example
DATA DIVISION.
WORKING-STORAGE SECTION.
01 Character-Name PIC X(15) VALUE "Hero".
01 Health-Points PIC 9(3) VALUE 100.
01 Magic-Points PIC 9(3) VALUE 50.
01 Experience PIC 9(5) VALUE 0.
01 Level PIC 9(2) VALUE 1.
@end example

What happens if you try to store "SuperLongCharacterName" in Character-Name?

@subsection Arrays: Storing Lists

Sometimes you need to store collections of data, like high scores or
inventory items.

@example
DATA DIVISION.
WORKING-STORAGE SECTION.
01 High-Scores PIC 9(5) OCCURS 10 TIMES.
01 Inventory PIC X(20) OCCURS 50 TIMES.

PROCEDURE DIVISION.
Store-High-Score.
    MOVE Player-Score TO High-Scores(1).
    GOBACK.
@end example

Access array elements with parentheses: @code{Array-Name(index)}

@strong{Note:} COBOL arrays are 1-based (start at 1, not 0 like some languages).

@section Making Your Program Do Things: Procedures

The PROCEDURE DIVISION is where the action happens - this is your
program's recipe steps. Here you write the instructions that tell
the computer what to do.

@subsection Basic Statements

COBOL statements read like English sentences. Here are the most common:

@table @code
@item MOVE source TO destination
Copy data from one place to another
@item ADD amount TO variable
Add numbers together
@item SUBTRACT amount FROM variable
Subtract numbers
@item DISPLAY message
Show text (for debugging)
@end table

@example
PROCEDURE DIVISION.
Setup-Game.
    MOVE 100 TO Player-Health.
    MOVE "Ready Player One" TO Game-Status.
    DISPLAY "Game initialized!".
    GOBACK.
@end example

@subsection Including Code: COPY Statements

Sometimes you want to reuse the same data definitions across multiple
programs. COBOL's COPY statement lets you include copybook files:

@example
IDENTIFICATION DIVISION.
PROGRAM-ID. Game-Logic.

DATA DIVISION.
WORKING-STORAGE SECTION.
COPY Game-Constants.     @c Include constants
COPY Player-Data.        @c Include player definitions

PROCEDURE DIVISION.
    MOVE Max-Health TO Player-Health
    GOBACK.
@end example

Copybooks use the WORKING-STORAGE SECTION with EXTERNAL data items
and USAGE BINARY for proper byte alignment:

@example
WORKING-STORAGE SECTION.
01  WS-SHARED-DATA EXTERNAL.
    05  Decal-XH USAGE BINARY 1.
    05  Player-Score USAGE BINARY 2.
@end example

Copybooks are searched for in the directories specified by the
@code{:include} parameter when compiling:

@example
(eightbol:compile-file "game-logic.cob"
                       :include '("Source/Generated" "Source/Classes"))
@end example

@subsection Organizing Code: Procedures

Procedures are like sub-recipes. Break complex tasks into smaller,
manageable pieces.

@example
PROCEDURE DIVISION.

Main-Game-Loop.
    PERFORM Handle-Input
    PERFORM Update-Game-State
    PERFORM Render-Screen
    PERFORM Check-Game-Over
    GOBACK.

Handle-Input.
    IF Button-A-Pressed THEN
        PERFORM Player-Jump
    END-IF
    GOBACK.

Player-Jump.
    ADD Jump-Power TO Player-Velocity-Y
    GOBACK.
@end example

Each procedure ends with GOBACK, which returns to the caller.

@subsection Making Decisions: IF Statements

Programs need to make choices based on conditions.

@example
IF Health-Points < 20 THEN
    DISPLAY "Low Health! Find healing!"
END-IF.
@end example

COBOL's IF statements read like English. You can include ELSE for alternatives:

@example
IF Enemy-Strength > Player-Level THEN
    PERFORM Run-Away
ELSE
    PERFORM Attack-Enemy
END-IF.
@end example

@subsection Repeating Actions: Loops

Games often repeat actions, like updating all enemies.

@table @code
@item PERFORM procedure
Call a procedure once
@item PERFORM procedure UNTIL condition
Repeat until condition is true
@item PERFORM procedure VARYING var FROM start BY step UNTIL end
Count through a range
@end table

@example
PERFORM Update-All-Enemies.

PERFORM Process-Game-Turn UNTIL Game-Over = 1.

PERFORM Check-Enemy VARYING I FROM 1 BY 1 UNTIL I > Enemy-Count.
@end example

@subsection Multiple Choices: EVALUATE

When you have many options, EVALUATE is cleaner than nested IFs:

@example
EVALUATE Player-Choice
    WHEN 1
        PERFORM Start-New-Game
    WHEN 2
        PERFORM Load-Saved-Game
    WHEN 3
        PERFORM Show-Options
    WHEN OTHER
        DISPLAY "Invalid choice!"
END-EVALUATE.
@end example

@subsection Game Programming Extensions

EIGHTBOL includes special features for game development:

@table @code
@item property OF object
Access object properties (like Player.Health)
@item INVOKE object "method"
Call object methods
@item CALL subroutine IN BANK bank
Banked memory calls
@item LOG FAULT "code"
Debug error logging
@end table

@example
INVOKE Player "TakeDamage" USING 25.

IF Health OF Player < 10 THEN
    LOG FAULT "LOWH"
END-IF.
@end example

@section Expressions and Conditions

@cindex expressions
@cindex conditions
@cindex operators

COBOL expressions compare values and combine conditions.

@subsection Comparison Operators

COBOL uses words for comparisons, making them readable:

@table @code
@item A = B
A equals B
@item A <> B
A is not equal to B
@item A < B
A is less than B
@item A > B
A is greater than B
@item A <= B
A is less than or equal to B
@item A >= B
A is greater than or equal to B
@end table

@example
IF Player-Score >= High-Score THEN
    MOVE Player-Name TO Champion-Name
END-IF.
@end example

@subsection Logical Operators

Combine conditions with AND, OR, and NOT:

@table @code
@item AND
Both conditions must be true
@item OR
At least one condition must be true
@item NOT
Reverse the condition
@end table

@example
IF Health > 0 AND Mana > 10 THEN
    DISPLAY "Ready to cast spell!"
END-IF.

IF NOT Game-Over THEN
    PERFORM Continue-Game
END-IF.
@end example

@subsection Complex Conditions

You can combine multiple conditions:

@example
IF Player-Level >= 5 AND Has-Magic-Sword = 'Y' OR Is-Cheat-Mode = 1 THEN
    PERFORM Unlock-Secret-Level
END-IF.
@end example

@strong{Remember:} AND is evaluated before OR. Use parentheses if needed.

@section Doing Math: Arithmetic

COBOL provides several ways to calculate:

@example
ADD 100 TO Player-Score.

SUBTRACT Damage FROM Health-Points.

MULTIPLY Attack-Power BY 2 GIVING Total-Damage.

COMPUTE Final-Score = Base-Score + (Bonus * Multiplier).
@end example

@subsection Arithmetic Operations

@table @asis
@item ADD source TO destination
Add to existing value
@item ADD source TO destination GIVING result
Add and store in new variable
@item SUBTRACT source FROM destination
Subtract from existing value
@item MULTIPLY source BY destination
Multiply values
@item DIVIDE source INTO destination
Divide values
@item COMPUTE result = expression
Complex calculations
@end table

@subsection Try This: Score Calculation

@example
COMPUTE Final-Score = Base-Score + (Time-Bonus * 10) - Penalties.

COMPUTE Average-Damage = Total-Damage / Hit-Count.
@end example

@section Built-in Functions

@cindex functions
@cindex RANDOM
@cindex WHEN-COMPILED

EIGHTBOL provides special functions for game programming:

@table @code
@item RANDOM
Generate a random number (0-255)
@item RANDOM(seed)
Generate seeded random number
@item WHEN-COMPILED
Get compilation timestamp
@end table

@example
COMPUTE Random-Direction = RANDOM.

IF RANDOM > 128 THEN
    PERFORM Move-Right
ELSE
    PERFORM Move-Left
END-IF.
@end example

@section Common Programming Patterns

Here are patterns you'll use frequently:

@subsection Game Loop Pattern

@example
PROCEDURE DIVISION.
Main-Loop.
    PERFORM Read-Input
    PERFORM Update-Objects
    PERFORM Draw-Screen
    IF NOT Game-Over THEN
        GO TO Main-Loop
    END-IF
    PERFORM Show-Game-Over
    GOBACK.
@end example

@subsection State Machine Pattern

@example
EVALUATE Game-State
    WHEN 1  @c Title Screen
        PERFORM Show-Title
    WHEN 2  @c Playing
        PERFORM Run-Game
    WHEN 3  @c Game Over
        PERFORM Show-Results
END-EVALUATE.
@end example

@subsection Input Handling Pattern

@example
Check-Input.
    IF Left-Pressed THEN
        SUBTRACT 1 FROM Player-X
    END-IF
    IF Right-Pressed THEN
        ADD 1 TO Player-X
    END-IF
    IF Jump-Pressed AND On-Ground THEN
        MOVE 'Y' TO Is-Jumping
    END-IF
    GOBACK.
@end example

@section Best Practices

As you write more COBOL, follow these guidelines:

@enumerate
@item Use descriptive variable names (Player-Health, not PH)
@item Add comments explaining complex logic
@item Break large procedures into smaller ones
@item Initialize variables with VALUE clauses
@item Test procedures individually before combining
@item Use PERFORM instead of GO TO when possible
@item Keep procedures under 50 lines when practical
@end enumerate

