@node Examples
@chapter Examples

@cindex examples
@cindex sample programs

Let's learn by doing! This chapter provides complete, working examples
you can compile and run. Start with simple programs and build up to
more complex ones.

@section Your First Program: Hello World

@example
IDENTIFICATION DIVISION.
PROGRAM-ID. Hello-Gamer.

PROCEDURE DIVISION.
Main-Program.
    DISPLAY "Welcome to EIGHTBOL Gaming!"
    DISPLAY "Ready Player One..."
    GOBACK.

END PROGRAM Hello-Gamer.
@end example

@strong{Try This:} Compile and run this program. What happens when you
add more DISPLAY statements?

@section Simple Calculator

Let's create a program that does basic math:

@example
IDENTIFICATION DIVISION.
PROGRAM-ID. Simple-Calculator.

DATA DIVISION.
WORKING-STORAGE SECTION.
01 Number-A PIC 9(3) VALUE 10.
01 Number-B PIC 9(3) VALUE 5.
01 Result PIC 9(3).

PROCEDURE DIVISION.
Main-Calculator.
    ADD Number-A TO Number-B GIVING Result
    DISPLAY "10 + 5 = " Result

    SUBTRACT Number-B FROM Number-A GIVING Result
    DISPLAY "10 - 5 = " Result

    MULTIPLY Number-A BY Number-B GIVING Result
    DISPLAY "10 * 5 = " Result

    GOBACK.

END PROGRAM Simple-Calculator.
@end example

@strong{Modify It:} Change the numbers and add division.

@section Simple Game Character

Let's create a character that can take damage:

@example
IDENTIFICATION DIVISION.
CLASS-ID. Game-Character INHERITS Basic-Object.

*--- FACTORY: Class-level data and methods ---
FACTORY.
    DATA DIVISION.
    WORKING-STORAGE SECTION.
    01 Next-Character-ID PIC 9(5) VALUE 1000.

    PROCEDURE DIVISION.
        IDENTIFICATION DIVISION.
        METHOD-ID. "Create-Character".
        DATA DIVISION.
        LINKAGE SECTION.
        01 aCharacter USAGE OBJECT REFERENCE Game-Character.
        PROCEDURE DIVISION RETURNING aCharacter.
            INVOKE SELF "New" RETURNING aCharacter
            ADD 1 TO Next-Character-ID
            EXIT METHOD.
        END METHOD "Create-Character".
END FACTORY.

*--- OBJECT: Instance-level data and methods ---
OBJECT.
    DATA DIVISION.
    WORKING-STORAGE SECTION.
    01 Character-Name PIC X(15) VALUE "Hero".
    01 Health-Points PIC 9(3) VALUE 100.
    01 Max-Health PIC 9(3) VALUE 100.
    01 Experience PIC 9(5) VALUE 0.

    PROCEDURE DIVISION.

        METHOD-ID. "Take-Damage".
        DATA DIVISION.
        LINKAGE SECTION.
        01 Damage-Amount PIC 9(3).
        PROCEDURE DIVISION USING BY VALUE Damage-Amount.
            SUBTRACT Damage-Amount FROM Health-Points
            IF Health-Points < 1 THEN
                INVOKE SELF "Die"
            ELSE
                DISPLAY Character-Name " has " Health-Points " health left."
            END-IF
            EXIT METHOD.
        END METHOD "Take-Damage".

        METHOD-ID. "Heal".
        DATA DIVISION.
        LINKAGE SECTION.
        01 Heal-Amount PIC 9(3).
        PROCEDURE DIVISION USING BY VALUE Heal-Amount.
            ADD Heal-Amount TO Health-Points
            IF Health-Points > Max-Health THEN
                MOVE Max-Health TO Health-Points
            END-IF
            DISPLAY Character-Name " healed to " Health-Points " health."
            EXIT METHOD.
        END METHOD "Heal".

        METHOD-ID. "Die".
        PROCEDURE DIVISION.
            DISPLAY Character-Name " has died!"
            LOG FAULT "DEAD"
            EXIT METHOD.
        END METHOD "Die".
END OBJECT.

END CLASS Game-Character.
@end example

@section Complete Game: Number Guessing

Here's a complete, playable game:

@example
IDENTIFICATION DIVISION.
PROGRAM-ID. Number-Guessing-Game.

DATA DIVISION.
WORKING-STORAGE SECTION.
01 Secret-Number PIC 9(3).
01 Player-Guess PIC 9(3).
01 Guess-Count PIC 9(2) VALUE 0.
01 Game-Over PIC X VALUE 'N'.
01 Guess-Message PIC X(30).

PROCEDURE DIVISION.
Main-Game.
    PERFORM Initialize-Game
    PERFORM Play-Game UNTIL Game-Over = 'Y'
    PERFORM Show-Final-Score
    GOBACK.

Initialize-Game.
    COMPUTE Secret-Number = RANDOM
    DISPLAY "I've picked a number between 0 and 255."
    DISPLAY "Can you guess it?"
    GOBACK.

Play-Game.
    DISPLAY "Enter your guess:"
    @c In a real game, you'd read input here
    COMPUTE Player-Guess = 50  @c Placeholder guess

    ADD 1 TO Guess-Count

    IF Player-Guess = Secret-Number THEN
        MOVE "Correct! You win!" TO Guess-Message
        MOVE 'Y' TO Game-Over
    ELSE
        IF Player-Guess < Secret-Number THEN
            MOVE "Too low! Try higher." TO Guess-Message
        ELSE
            MOVE "Too high! Try lower." TO Guess-Message
        END-IF
    END-IF

    DISPLAY Guess-Message
    DISPLAY "Guesses so far: " Guess-Count
    GOBACK.

Show-Final-Score.
    DISPLAY "Game completed in " Guess-Count " guesses!"
    IF Guess-Count < 5 THEN
        DISPLAY "Excellent guessing!"
    ELSE
        IF Guess-Count < 10 THEN
            DISPLAY "Good job!"
        ELSE
            DISPLAY "Better luck next time!"
        END-IF
    END-IF
    GOBACK.

END PROGRAM Number-Guessing-Game.
@end example

@section Tips for Writing Your Own Programs

As you write more COBOL programs, here are some helpful tips:

@enumerate
@item Start simple - get one feature working at a time
@item Use DISPLAY statements to debug your program
@item Test procedures individually before combining them
@item Keep procedures short and focused on one task
@item Use meaningful variable names
@item Initialize variables with VALUES
@item Comment complex logic
@item Experiment with different approaches
@end enumerate

@strong{Remember:} Every expert programmer started as a beginner. The key
is to practice regularly and learn from each program you write!

@node Troubleshooting
@chapter Troubleshooting

@cindex troubleshooting
@cindex errors
@cindex debugging

Common issues and their solutions.

@section Compilation Errors

@subsection Undefined Variable
@code{MOVE 1 TO UndefinedVar} generates an error because the variable
isn't declared in DATA DIVISION.

@strong{Solution:} Declare all variables in WORKING-STORAGE SECTION.

@subsection Invalid PIC Clause
String variables (PIC X) are not supported.

@strong{Solution:} Use byte arrays or numeric variables instead.

@section Runtime Issues

@subsection Stack Overflow
Deep recursion can cause stack overflow on 8-bit systems.

@strong{Solution:} Use iteration instead of recursion where possible.

@subsection Memory Limits
8-bit systems have limited RAM.

@strong{Solution:} Minimize variable usage and optimize data structures.

@section Platform-Specific Issues

@subsection 6502 Zero Page
6502 code uses zero-page addressing for efficiency.

@subsection Z80 Memory Banking
Z80 systems may require bank switching for large programs.

